Peel and chop your @onion{1} into 2cm pieces and peel and finely chop your @garlic{2%cloves}. Grate the @mature cheddar cheese{1%block} and set aside.

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees.

Heat @oil{1%tbsp} in a pan on a medium heat and fry the onion and garlic gently for about ~{5%mins} until softened. Add the @British beef mince{500%g}, turn the heat up slightly and cook for ~{10%mins}, stirring occasionally until the mince is browned all over.

Boil 100ml of water and dissolve the @beef stock pot{1} in this. Add half the @chopped tomatoes{1%400g can}, stock and @tomato purée{1%tbsp} to the pan and stir well. Add the @smoked paprika{1/2%tsp}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and some @pepper{} to the pan and simmer for ~{5%mins} on medium-low heat, until thickened.

Cut the @flour tortillas{8} in half. Share the mince mixture between the tortillas and spread over each tortilla half. Roll up to enclose the meat and pack all your rolls tightly in an #ovenproof dish{}.

Put a #pot{} of water on to boil and then spoon the remaining tinned tomatoes over the tortilla rolls.

Put your @creme fraiche{1} in a #bowl{} and add in three quarters of the grated cheddar. Stir together, then spoon the cheesy mixture over the tortillas, scatter the remaining cheese over the top. Pop in the oven on a high shelf for ~{10-15%mins}, until golden brown.

Cut the tops and bottoms off the @green beans{2}. Tip: This is called top and tailing! Cut them in half and add to the boiling water. Simmer for ~{3-5%mins}, until just tender. Drain and serve with the beef roly polys.

> Get your sombreros out, wrap yourself in a stripy blanket and get ready for a Mexican style meal. Flour tortillas stuffed with tasty mince and smothered in a cheesy sauce… making your mouth water? Get the kids to help with prep, whether it's grating cheese or rolling up tortillas, they will be sure to enjoy their roly polys if they've had a hand in making them. Don't forget the cold beers and slice of lime!